{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"00bfb742-fa53-4034-b831-7576785ea654","content":"Two things change with xUnit.net v3 + MTP:\n\n### 1. Filter syntax changes\n\nThe VSTest `--filter` syntax (`FullyQualifiedName~X&Category=Y`) doesn't work with MTP. Use the new `--filter` format with **`/`-prefixed properties**:\n\n```bash\ndotnet test --filter \"FullyQualifiedName~IntegrationTests&Category=Smoke\"\n# becomes ↓\ndotnet test -- --filter \"FullyQualifiedName~IntegrationTests\" --filter \"Category=Smoke\"\n```\n\nWith MTP, each `--filter` after `--` is an **AND** condition. The `~` (contains) operator is supported for `FullyQualifiedName`. Trait filters use `key=value` syntax directly.\n\nAlternatively, you can use the single combined form:\n\n```bash\ndotnet test -- --filter \"FullyQualifiedName~IntegrationTests & Category=Smoke\"\n```\n\n### 2. `[Trait]` → built-in `[Category]` (optional but recommended)\n\nxUnit.net v3 has a first-class `[Category]` attribute, so you can simplify:\n\n```csharp\n// Old: [Trait(\"Category\", \"Smoke\")]\n// New:\n[Category(\"Smoke\")]\n```\n\nBoth forms work for filtering — `[Trait(\"Category\", \"Smoke\")]` is still supported in v3.\n\n### Key differences summary\n\n| VSTest (v2) | MTP (v3) |\n|---|---|\n| `--filter \"prop~val\"` | `-- --filter \"prop~val\"` |\n| `A&B` in one string | separate `--filter` per condition, or `&` inside quotes |\n| `Category=Smoke` (from Trait) | `Category=Smoke` (same, works with both `[Trait]` and `[Category]`) |","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"c2bbac95-299a-408b-8500-7100089a786d","outputTokens":459,"requestId":"67C0:1E3875:2A06AAE:2E6A81B:69FD3729"},"id":"5c9f5751-ca7b-43c1-a9eb-881df0616247","timestamp":"2026-05-08T01:07:01.739Z","parentId":"66b71547-ed22-44e4-950b-d4ecb25c06b9"}
